PROMPT START

You are turning the following blog into a simple, skimmable, high-impact email written specifically for franchisors.

Your goal is to extract the 5 biggest insights and rewrite them in ultra-simple layman’s terms, so a franchisor can read the email in seconds and understand exactly why it matters.

AUDIENCE

Franchisors, multi-brand operators, and founders who want to:

Protect their system

Reduce liability

Strengthen insurance requirements

Protect franchisee investments

Scale with fewer surprises

They skim everything.
Your writing must be instantly understandable.

NON-NEGOTIABLE RULES
1. No jargon at all

Everything must be written like you’re explaining it to someone outside the insurance industry.

2. No acronyms on first mention

If the blog includes a coverage type or insurance term, you must:

A) Write out the full coverage name the FIRST time
B) After that, you MAY use the acronym

No exceptions.

3. Define each coverage ONCE at the bottom of the email

Definitions should be in their own section at the end

One sentence each

Written at a 5th–6th grade reading level

Must be simple, clear, and human

NO repeating definitions anywhere else

Definitions do NOT count toward bullet limits

EMAIL STRUCTURE & RULES
1. Subject Line

Must be:

2–6 words

Curiosity-based

Emotionally compelling

Relevant to franchisor risk or system protection

Following Neil Patel best practices (short, punchy, intriguing)

Examples to mimic (do not reuse):

“Your Hidden Risk”

“The Gap That Hurts”

“A Costly Blind Spot”

“Before This Breaks You”

“What Most Brands Miss”

2. Intro (2 sentences max)

Follow StoryBrand:

Sentence 1: Name the one problem the blog helps franchisors solve.

Sentence 2: Explain why it matters for protecting their brand or franchisees.

3. Top 5 Takeaways

Create five bullets, each:

Under 14 words

One simple idea

Written in plain English

High-level only

Built around risk, protection, clarity, or system stability

Able to stand alone as a “headline insight”

No definitions inside the bullets

Use acronyms only after the coverage has been written out once

4. Coverage Definitions (end of email)

At the bottom, add a small section titled:

Definitions (in simple terms):

List each coverage once, only if used in the email.

Use this format:

General Liability Insurance: coverage that protects the business if someone gets hurt or property is damaged.
Employment Practices Liability Insurance: coverage that protects the business from things like discrimination, sexual harassment, or wrongful termination.
(etc.)

Definitions must be:

One sentence

Ultra-simple

No jargon

5. Closing CTA

Use this EXACT text:

If you want the full breakdown so you can protect your brand and your franchisees, you can read the full article here: [Insert Link]

FINAL OUTPUT FORMAT

Return the finished email like this:

Subject: [High-hook subject line]

Hi there,

[2-sentence intro]

Top 5 takeaways:

[Bullet #1]

[Bullet #2]

[Bullet #3]

[Bullet #4]

[Bullet #5]

If you want the full breakdown so you can protect your brand and your franchisees, you can read the full article here: [Insert Link]

Definitions (in simple terms):
[Only list the coverages used in the email. Define each once, in one simple sentence.]

Now rewrite the blog below following ALL rules above:
[PASTE BLOG HERE]

PROMPT END
